Germany: a budget fetish that is costly
FRANKFURT – The European Central Bank (ECB) is facing fierce attacks in Germany, a country that has long prided itself on defending the principle of central bank independence.
It was actually Germany that insisted on this principle being included in the criteria set out by the Maastricht Treaty, which establish the conditions for membership in the European Monetary Union.
For many members of the Economic and Monetary Union (EMU), the decision to grant independence to their central bank in order to join the eurozone implied a political regime change.
Thus, the independence of the Bank of France during the referendum on ratification of the Maastricht Treaty in 1992 was one of the strongest arguments in the campaign against joining the euro.
In today's Germany, on the other hand, it has become commonplace, so to speak, to pressure the central bank.
For several months now, even the Finance Minister, Wolfgang Schäuble, has regularly commented on the monetary policy of the European Central Bank (ECB).
Schaüble's interventions target the very core of what constitutes the independence of the central bank.
If he does not seek to redefine the objective of monetary policy (this "price norm," in the old terminology of the Bundesbank), he nevertheless offers his advice on the tools the ECB should use and how it should manage them to achieve such an objective.
There are precedents.
In 1998, Oskar Lafontaine, then Germany's Minister of Finance, gave good advice to the first president of the ECB, Wim Duisenberg, on how to conduct monetary policy (Lafontaine's goal was ultimately to create a target zone for exchange rates).
Duisenberg, with typically Dutch brevity, replied that there was nothing incongruous about a politician expressing his opinion on monetary policy (in Germany, this was absolutely unusual). "Nevertheless," he added, "it would be entirely abnormal to take [his] suggestions into account."
Sure! Please provide the French sentence you'd like translated into English.
Respect for the independence of monetary policy has long been a central element of the German Stabilitätkultur ("culture of stability").
The founding act of the Bundesbank's acquired reputation for strict independence was its refusal to yield to the exhortations of Chancellor Konrad Adenauer, who wanted it to contain the rise in interest rates in 1956.
At that time, France did not see things the same way.
Charles de Gaulle was on the verge of creating the Fifth Republic, with a French Bank that was accountable to the Minister of Finance.
But it was another time.
Following the various crises that have shaken the UEM, monetary policy has increasingly tended to replace fiscal policy.
Has the old doctrine become obsolete?
Europe remains highly vulnerable; the median inhabitant of the EU has already lost ten years, and what is even more alarming, we are approaching a critical situation.
Yet, the United States do better.
Despite a politically difficult situation to manage, they managed to address the macroeconomic problem (weak aggregate demand) they faced by implementing expansionary fiscal and monetary policies.
The United States also managed their banking problems more effectively, which were initially much more severe than in Europe.
(There is obviously a strong interaction between the measures that can be taken in the two areas.)
The more robust an economy is, the more profitable its banks are and the more capable they are of fulfilling their function: financing the economy.
But the independence of the ECB is less threatened by the good advice of a finance minister than by the lack of support from the population.
And indeed, the famous autonomy of the Bundesbank relied less on its legal status than on the unwavering support (justified by its performance) of German citizens.
It is exactly the opposite with the ECB.
Voices are being heard, notably in Germany, calling for it to face greater pressure.
But the greatest threat to the ECB's autonomy comes from the unbearable burden that weighs on its shoulders.
The less fiscal policy is used to stabilize output, the more central banks are de facto forced to take on this objective (unless, of course, they are designed to let nature take its course and allow the economy to fall into stagnation, or even worse).
The political outcome of this chain of events is a very clear regression toward nationalism, both right-wing and left-wing, in all the countries of the Eurozone, including Germany.
The rise of nationalism is almost a logical corollary of the policies pursued.
It is endogenous.
And there too, Germany is leading the way, with its obsession for the schwarze Null, for budgetary balance, come what may.
In Germany, deficits are viewed unfavorably, not only from an arithmetic perspective but also from a moral standpoint, even though this defies economic common sense and resembles clientelism.
At the end of the nineteenth century, leading German specialists in public finance, including Albert Schäffle and Adolph Wagner, formulated a "golden rule" stating that current expenditures should, on average, be financed by current revenues.
Public expenditures, and the resources they require, are justified by their usefulness.
This means that investments aimed at improving productivity—equipment expenditures—can be financed through debt, the servicing of which is ensured by the growth of income and the tax base associated with it.
This classical approach has been institutionalized in a useful concept: the distinction between current expenditures and investment expenditures, which is still practiced at the municipal level in Germany (and Austria).
It is crucial, because in Germany, about 50% of public sector investment expenditures are managed at this level (a proportion that has been decreasing, as the municipal share was two-thirds at the beginning of the 1990s).
These expenditures are consistent with the support for the competitiveness of German small and medium-sized enterprises (Mittelstand).
But compared to the early 1990s and at constant prices, investment spending has decreased by about 15%.
More than a decade ago, they were insufficient to maintain the capital stock.
If this is not how we prepare for the future, this is how we undermine productivity and prosperity.
In short, the black zero goes against the intended goal.
The aging infrastructure (surely not as bad as in the United States) has become a real problem for Germany.
Furthermore, the budgetary frugality of German leaders goes beyond Germany's borders, and its effects are amplified by the monetary union, which does not have exchange rates to accommodate national particularities.
Of course, the European monetary union is imperfect.
But turning into a scapegoat the only institution willing to "do what it takes" to get the UEM back on track is a very bad idea.
That governments use, where it exists, the budgetary space they have to relieve pressure on the ECB would be a much better strategy.
Germany, without a doubt, has a certain margin of maneuver in this regard.
